# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rollover-fire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The idea of fighting forest fires from the air dates back at least as far as Friedrich Karl von Koenig-Warthausen's observations on seeing a blaze when overflying the Santa Lucia Range, California, in 1929.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of terminology has been used in the popular media for the aircraft (and methods) used in aerial firefighting.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The terms **airtanker** or **air tanker** generally refer to fixed-wing aircraft based in the United States; "airtanker" is used in official documentation.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The term "**waterbomber**" is used in some Canadian government documents for the same class of vehicles, though it sometimes has a connotation of amphibians.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft are used for aerial firefighting.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management own, lease, or contract for nearly 1,000 aircraft each fire season, with annual expenditures in excess of US$250 million in recent years".
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters may be fitted with tanks (helitankers) or they may carry buckets.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Some helitankers, such as the Erickson AirCrane, are also outfitted with a front-mounted foam cannon.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Buckets are usually filled by submerging or dipping them in lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or portable tanks.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The most popular of the buckets is the flexible Bambi Bucket.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Tanks can be filled on the ground (by water tenders or truck-mounted systems) or water can be siphoned from lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or a portable tank through a hanging snorkel.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Currently the world's largest helicopter, the Mil Mi-26, uses a Bambi bucket.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Mendocino Air Tanker Squad formed by Joseph Bolles Ely in 1956 was the first such unit in the United States to drop water and retardant on fires.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Based at the Willows-Glenn County Airport it soon led the way for other agencies to form similar squads.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Though World War II- and Korean War-era bombers were for a long time the mainstay of the aerial firefighting fleet, newer purpose-built tankers have since come online.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The smallest are the Single Engine Air Tankers (SEATs).
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] These are agricultural sprayers that generally drop about 800 US gallons (3,000 L) of water or retardant.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Examples include the Air Tractor AT-802, which can deliver around 800 gallons of water or fire retardant solution in each drop, and the Soviet Antonov An-2 biplane.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Both of these aircraft can be fitted with floats that scoop water from the surface of a body of water.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Similar in configuration to the World War II–era Consolidated PBY Catalina, the Canadair CL-215 and its derivative the CL-415 are designed and built specifically for firefighting.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Croatian Air Force uses six CL-415s as well as six AT 802s for firefighting purposes.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Conair also converted a number of Convair 580 and Fokker F27 Friendship turboprop airliners to air tankers.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The largest aerial firefighter ever used is a Boeing 747 aerial firefighter, known as the Global Supertanker, that can carry 19,600 US gallons (74,200 L) fed by a pressurized drop system.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Supertanker was deployed operationally for the first time in 2009, fighting a fire in Spain.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The tanker made its first American operation on August 31, 2009, at the Oak Glen Fire.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] It has since been replaced by a Boeing 747-400.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Another wide body jetliner that is currently being used as an air tanker is the modified McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30 operated by the 10 Tanker Air Carrier company as the DC-10 Air Tanker.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] It can carry up to 12,000 US gallons (45,400 L) of fire fighting retardant.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Russian Ministry of Emergency Situations operates convertible-to-cargo Ilyushin Il-76 airtankers that have been operating with 11,000-US-gallon (41,600 L) tanking systems, and several Beriev Be-200 jet powered amphibian aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Be-200 can carry a maximum payload of about 12,000 litres (3,200 US gal) of water, making "scoops" in suitable stretches of water in 14 seconds.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Bombardier's Dash 8 Q Series aircraft are the basis of new, next-generation air tankers.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Cascade Aerospace has converted two pre-owned Q400s to act as part-time water bomber and part-time transport aircraft for France's Sécurité Civile, while Neptune Aviation is converting a pre-owned Q300 as a prototype to augment its Lockheed P-2 Neptune aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Sécurité Civile also operates twelve Canadair CL-415 and nine Conair Turbo Firecat aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Neptune Aviation also currently operates converted British Aerospace 146 jetliners as air tankers.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The BAe 146 can carry up to 3,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray USA Ltd. of Chico, California has also converted the BAe 146 jetliner to the role of air tanker.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Another modern-era passenger aircraft that has now been converted for aerial firefighting missions in the U.S. is the McDonnell Douglas MD-87 jetliner operated by Erickson Aero Tanker.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The MD-87 can carry up to 4,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Coulson Aviation unveiled a Boeing 737-300 firefighting conversion in May 2017.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Six aircraft have been purchased from Southwest Airlines for the RADS system conversion which was planned to enter service in December 2017.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The 737 aircraft is smaller than the C-130Q which allows for a wider range of airfields to be utilized.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Britt Coulson further stated the aircraft will be able to retain the current seat and galley configuration for tanker operations.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] On 22 November 2018, the 737 was used for the first time to fight a fire near Newcastle, Australia.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] In July 2022, Airbus tested the aerial firefighting capacity of the A400M using a roll-on/roll-off kit comprising a 20-tonne water tank and piping allowing the load to be expelled from the end of the cargo ramp.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] All links, citations and data sources are listed in the paragraph above.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] For accident and grounding citations, see paragraph below table.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Other former military aircraft utilized as firefighting air tankers in the U.S. in the past included the B-17 and the PB4Y-2, a version of the B-24.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Lead Plane function directs the activities of the airtankers by both verbal target descriptions and by physically leading the airtankers on the drop run.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The leadplane is typically referred to as a "Bird Dog" in Canada or "Supervision" aircraft in Australia.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The O-2 Skymaster, Cessna 310 and OV-10 Bronco have been used as spotter and lead plane platforms.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources has also used the Cessna 337.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Beechcraft Baron was long used as a leadplane or air attack ship, but most were retired in 2003; more common now is the Beechcraft King Air and the Twin Commander 690.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] A Cessna Citation 500 jet owned by Air Spray (1967) LTd. was used by the British Columbia Ministry of Forests beginning in 1995 and used for two fire seasons to lead the very fast Electra L188 air tanker to the fires.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] This was the first time a jet aircraft was used as a lead plane or "bird dog".
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Department of Parks and Wildlife in Western Australia operates a fleet of nine American Champion Scouts 8GCBC during the summer months as spotter aircraft and Air Attack platforms.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The Provinces of Alberta and British Columbia and the Yukon Territories contract to supply Twin Commander 690 as bird dog aircraft for their air tanker fleets.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray owns 9 Twin Commander 690 for use as bird dog aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] In the United States, most of these aircraft are privately owned and contracted to government agencies, and the National Guard and the U.S.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Marines also maintain fleets of firefighting aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service (USFS) and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) announced that they were cancelling contracts with operators of 33 heavy airtankers.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] They cited liability concerns and an inability to safely manage the fleet after the wing failure and resulting crash of a C-130A Hercules in California and a PB4Y-2 in Colorado during the summer of 2002.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Both aged aircraft broke up in flight due to catastrophic fatigue cracks at the wing roots.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] After subsequent third-party examination and extensive testing of all USFS contracted heavy airtankers, three companies were awarded contracts and now maintain a combined fleet of 23 aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Borate salts used in the past to fight wildfires have been found to sterilize the soil and be toxic to animals so are now prohibited.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Newer retardants use ammonium sulfate or ammonium polyphosphate with attapulgite clay thickener or diammonium phosphate with a guar gum derivative thickener.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants often contain wetting agents, preservatives and rust inhibitors and are colored red with ferric oxide or fugitive color to mark where they have been dropped.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Brand names of fire retardants for aerial application include Fortress and Phos-Chek.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Some water-dropping aircraft carry tanks of a guar gum derivative to thicken the water and reduce runoff.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters can hover over the fire and drop water or retardant.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The S-64 Helitanker has microprocessor-controlled doors on its tank.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] The doors are controlled based on the area to be covered and wind conditions.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Fixed-wing aircraft must make a pass and drop water or retardant like a bomber.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Water is not usually dropped directly on flames because its effect is short-lived.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants are not typically used to extinguish the fire, but instead are used to contain the fire, or slow it down to allow ground crews to contain it.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Because of this, retardants are usually dropped in front of or around a moving fire, rather than directly on it, creating a firebreak.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Aerial firefighting is most effectively used in conjunction with ground-based efforts, as aircraft are only one weapon in the firefighting arsenal.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] However, there have been cases of aircraft extinguishing fires long before ground crews were able to reach them.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] Some firefighting aircraft can refill their tanks in mid-flight, by flying down to skim the surface of large bodies of water.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] This is particularly useful in rural areas where flying back to an airbase for refills may take too much time.
[src:rollover-fire/aerial-firefighting] In 2002 an Ontario CL-415 crew was able to refill 100 times within a 4-hour mission, delivering 162,000 US gallons (613,240 L) or 1,350,000 pounds (612 t) of water on a fire near Dryden, Ontario (June 1, 2002 Dryden fire # 10 Tanker #271 civil ident C-GOGE).
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports with scheduled passenger flights are obliged to have firefighters and firefighting apparatus on location ready for duty any time aircraft operate.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports may have regulatory oversight by an arm of their individual national governments or voluntarily under standards of the International Civil Aviation Organization.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the mass casualty potential of an aviation emergency, the speed with which emergency response equipment and personnel arrive at the scene of the emergency is of paramount importance.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Their arrival and initial mission to secure the aircraft against all hazards, particularly fire, increases the survivability of the passengers and crew on board.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airport firefighters have advanced training in the application of firefighting foams, dry chemical and clean agents used to extinguish burning aviation fuel in and around an aircraft in order to maintain a path for evacuating passengers to exit the fire hazard area.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Further, should fire either be encountered in the cabin or extend there from an external fire, the ARFF responders must work to control/extinguish these fires as well.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Primary to the hazard mitigation and safe evacuation of ambulatory passengers is the need to perform rescue operations.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Passengers unable to extricate themselves must be removed from the aircraft and provided medical care.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] This process is extremely labor-intensive, requiring both firefighters and support personnel.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the nature of a mass casualty incident, rescue workers employ triage to classify the victims and direct their efforts where they can maximize survival.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Subsequent to the emergency being declared under control, the ARFF function reverts to one of protecting the scene, eliminating any peripheral or slowly evolving hazards and assisting to preserve the scene for investigators.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] In 2016, an Emirati fire fighter died from burns when trying to fight the fire in the Emirates Flight 521 crash.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the rarity of aircraft fires, firefighters often have other usual duties such as luggage loaders or security guards, which they have to abandon at fire alarms.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Specialized fire apparatus are required for the ARFF function, the design of which is predicated on many factors but primarily: speed, water-carrying capacity, off-road performance, and agent discharge rates.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Since an accident could occur anywhere on or off airport property, sufficient water and other agents must be carried to contain the fire to allow for the best possibility of extinguishment, maximum possibility for evacuation and/or until additional resources arrive on the scene.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] They also must wear self-contained breathing apparatus to provide a source of clean air, enabling them to work in the presence of smoke or other super-heated gases, such as when making entry into the burning cabin of an aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) mandates ARFF operations at all U.S. airports that serve scheduled passenger air carriers.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] These are the only civilian fire protection services that are specifically regulated by any governmental entity.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Military bases may have their own ARFF services with specialized duties and training.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports required to have ARFF services are inspected at least annually by the FAA for compliance with FAR, Part 139.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Military ARFF operations must meet the mission requirements for their individual branch of the service.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] In many cases the FAA will perform the investigatory duties after an incident, but in instances where significant injuries or any fatal accident the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) will investigate and the ARFF contingent will assist where needed.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] An index is assigned to each FAA Part 139 certificate holder based on a combination of the air carrier aircraft length and the average number of daily departures.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] If the longest air carrier aircraft at the airport has five or more average daily departures, the matching index is used.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] If the longest aircraft has less than five average daily departures, the next lower index is used.
[src:rollover-fire/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] That index determines the required number of ARFF vehicles and required amount of extinguishing agents.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] An **airport crash tender** (known in some countries as an **airport fire appliance**) is a specialised fire engine designed for use in aircraft firefighting at aerodromes, airports, and military air bases.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] They can be mounted on 4x4, 6x6, or even 8x8 wheeled chassis.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] In order to decrease their turning radius, all four of the 8x8 wheeled unit's front wheels may be steerable.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Newer airport crash tenders also incorporate twin-agent nozzles/injection systems to inject a stream of Purple-K dry chemical into the AFFF firefighting foam stream, helping to extinguish the fire faster.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Some also have Halotron tanks with handlines for situations that require a clean agent to be utilized.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] These features allow airport crash tenders to reach an aircraft quickly, and rapidly put out large fires with jet fuel involved.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Some tenders have an elevated extended extinguishing arm capable of raising a water/foam cannon up to about 10–20 m (33–66 ft).
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Some can then puncture superficial structures of an aeroplane to fight a fire inside the fuselage.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) has given standards and recommended practices on rescue fire fighting categories of civil aerodromes.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] National aviation authorities may have given even further requirements on aerodrome rescue and fire services.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] The rescue fire services are based on a critical aircraft size based on a statistical analysis of movements (take-offs and landings) on the airport.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] There are also minimum category levels based on e.g. the number of seats in the critical aircraft.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Depending on the airport category, the standards determine the minimum number of rescue fire-fighting vehicles.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] In addition, requirements are given on the water and foam capacities, discharge rates for foam solutions, and minimum dry chemical powder (complementary agent) amounts, reserve stocks of fire fighting agents, ability to operate on rough terrain, and acceleration of the air crash tenders.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] The end of each runway has to be reached in a response time of two minutes or less, and any part of the movement area has to be achieved in a response time not exceeding three minutes.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Airport rescue and firefighting services operate many specialist vehicles to provide emergency cover at airports.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] Domestic appliances are similar in function and appearance to fire appliances operated by local fire services.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] They are not as large or as heavy as airport crash tenders.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] The units are ordinarily used to respond to fire incidents in airport terminal buildings but also respond to aircraft incidents.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] The appliances carry breathing apparatus, rescue equipment, firefighting media, ladders, cutting equipment, etc.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] "*First attack*" or "*rapid intervention vehicles*" (RIV).
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] RIVs are normally smaller, nimble fire appliances capable of quick acceleration and high speed.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] They carry less equipment than domestic appliances and crash tenders but arrive first on scene at aircraft incidents to begin rescue and firefighting operations whilst heavier and larger units approach.
[src:rollover-fire/airport-crash-tender] *General purpose vehicles* (such as a fire chief's car or general purpose or incident support vehicles).
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] A **backdraft** (North American English), **backdraught** (British English) or **smoke explosion** is the abrupt burning of superheated gases in a fire caused when oxygen rapidly enters a hot, oxygen-depleted environment; for example, when a window or door to an enclosed space is opened or broken.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Backdrafts are typically seen as a blast of smoke and/or flame out of an opening of a building.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Backdrafts present a serious threat to firefighters.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] There is some debate concerning whether backdrafts should be considered a type of flashover.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] When material is heated enough, it begins to break down into smaller compounds, including flammable or even explosive gas, typically hydrocarbons.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] This is called pyrolysis, and does not require oxygen.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] If oxygen is also provided, then the hydrocarbons can combust, starting a fire.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] If material undergoing pyrolysis is later given sufficient oxygen, the hydrocarbons will ignite and, therefore, combustion takes place.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] A backdraft can occur when a compartment fire has little or no ventilation.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Due to this, little or no oxygen can flow into the compartment.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Then, because fires reduce oxygen, the oxygen concentration decreases.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] When the oxygen concentration becomes too low to support combustion, some or all of the combustion switches to pyrolysis.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Nonetheless, the hydrocarbons and smoke (primarily particulate matter) remain at a temperature hot enough to auto-ignite.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] The colour and movement of smoke is used by firefighters to infer fire conditions, including the risk of backdraft.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] This is an indication that the room lacks enough oxygen to permit oxidation of the soot particles.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Firefighters often look to see if there is soot on the inside of windows and in any cracks in the window (caused e.g. by the heat).
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] The windows may also have a slight vibration due to varying pressure within the compartment due to intermittent combustion.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] If firefighters discover a room sucking air into itself, for example through a crack, they generally evacuate immediately, because this is a strong indication that a backdraft is imminent.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Due to pressure differences, puffs of smoke are sometimes drawn back into the enclosed space from which they emanated, which is how the term *backdraft* originated.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Backdrafts are very dangerous, often surprising even experienced firefighters.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] The most common tactic used by firefighters to defuse a potential backdraft is to ventilate a room from its highest point, allowing the heat and smoke to escape without igniting.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] In common usage, the term flashover describes the near-simultaneous ignition of material caused by heat attaining the autoignition temperature of the combustible material and gases in an enclosure.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Flashovers according to this narrower definition, i.e. those caused by rising temperatures, would not be considered backdrafts since backdrafts are caused by the introduction of oxygen into an enclosed space with conditions already suitable for ignition, and are thus caused by chemical change.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] Backdrafts were publicized by the 1991 movie *Backdraft*, in which a serial arsonist in Chicago uses them as a means of assassinating conspirators in a scam.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] In the film adaptation of Stephen King's *1408*, the protagonist Mike Enslin induces one as a last-ditch effort to kill the room.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] The term is also used and is the title of a scene in the 2012 video game *Root Double: Before Crime * After Days*.
[src:rollover-fire/backdraft] In the second book of the light novel series Imperial Reincarnation: I Came, I Saw, I Survived, the character Carmine uses a magically produced backdraft to defend himself against an assassination attempt.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] A **barn fire**, also known as a **farm fire** or **stable fire** (especially when horses are affected), occurs when a barn or stable at a farm for the keeping of livestock catches fire, and is partially or wholly destroyed.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] This can lead to the death of animals, release of toxic fumes, and financial and material damage for insurers, owners, employees and nearby residents.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] According to Prevent Agri, there are still too few precautions taken against barn fires in Belgium.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Often there are no fire extinguishing devices present, and other safety measures are often foregone because of the financial cost to the livestock company, and one usually does not take potential accidents into account in administration.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Nor are there a reliable statistics on accidents, because CEOs are not obligated to register them; only employees do.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In June, Peeters responded that there had been 143 barn fires in all of Belgium between 1 May 2006 and 1 May 2011; in 62 of those cases, animals perished.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The death toll was 192,862 animals, including 27,851 pigs, 196 cattle, 164,000 poultry (rounded estimate, mainly chickens), 8 horses, 7 goats and a few rabbits.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Of all fires in Belgium, about 4% was a barn fire, which were mostly caused by electricity, overheating or short circuits in machines.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The Royal decree of 19 December 1997 regulates the fire safety of buildings; on 15 August 2009, it was expanded with appendix 6 which regulates the fire safety of industrial buildings, including buildings for the purpose of commercial animal husbandry.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Although appendix 6 contains stricter fire precautions than existed earlier, it only applies to newly built barns; barns built prior to 2009 are not yet required to comply with the new regulations.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Peeters closed by mentioning several potential safety precautions, but said that fire safety was a federal competence (and thus the Flemish Government did not have the authority to take additional measures).
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The Canadian Coalition for Farm Animals evaluates that 610,000 farm animals died in fires between January 2015 and October 2018, including 5,000 cattle, 13,000 turkeys, 82,000 pigs and 450,000 chickens.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The building codes of several provinces do not currently require barns to have heat detectors and alarm systems.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The provinces base their own codes on the National Research Council's National Farm Building Code.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] A new version of the Code is planned for 2020, but may not include additional safety systems, as barns are considered "low occupancy" buildings.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In any case, only new constructions are required to apply new standards.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In addition, fire prevention standards are included in the voluntary codes of practice published by the National Farm Animal Care Council, which are frequently put into practice by producers.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Animal deaths usually attract little attention from the media beyond local outlets, unless they involve pets or horses.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In Germany, fire alarm systems and fire sprinkler systems are mandatory.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Livestock barns tend to be very prone to fire because of the presence of dust, straw and manure gases, while barn roofs are often made of highly flammable pur foam, enabling fire to spread rapidly.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Air washing installations, which have been mandated by the government since 2012 for many animal husbandry companies in order to reduce ammonia emissions, are flammable because of electricity.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Moreover, the air ventilation system of air washers can fan the flames.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The fact that animals often have no place to flee in order to escape from a fire, and the fact that chicken's feathers are highly flammable themselves, further increases the risk of fatalities.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The huge increase in so-called "mega-barns" (featuring large numbers of animals packed together in a single building) from 2005 to 2013, which complicate the isolation and extinguishing of fires, also drives up the number of victims per catastrophe.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] All these factors combined resulted in the deaths of well over a million animals by barn fires in the Netherlands between 2006 and 2011.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Finally, many animals that survive a barn fire may be so poisoned by smoke that they still need to be culled anyway.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Because of a lack of safety precautions and government-designed regulations, many barn animals die which could have been saved.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] For example, emergency exits, sprinkler and alarm systems can be installed.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Some livestock farmers don't do this, however, because it often costs a lot of money and is not obligatory.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] As of 2011, according to the Dutch building code (Bouwbesluit), animals had the same status as office supplies and machines, and did not require extra protection.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The Dutch government, in cooperation with farmers, insurance companies, fire brigades and the Dutch Society for the Protection of Animals, enacted the Action Plan Barn Fires 2012–2016 'to considerably reduce the amount of barn fires and animal fire victims'.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The Building Code was amended in 2012 and again in 2014: henceforth, new barns had to be built using fire-resistant materials and fire compartments, and there had to be firewater present.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] However, the action plan appeared not to work: the number of barn fires and animal victims rose even further.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Besides, the new fire safety requirements only applied to barns built after 2014; older barns (15,500 of the circa 16,550) remained just as unsafe as before, and in the 2014–2017 period by far the most fires occurred in barns constructed before 2014.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] By 2017, there was still no requirement for the installation of fire alarm and sprinkler systems or emergency exits for animals.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Amongst others, the Wakker Dier foundation and the Party for the Animals (PvdD) campaigned for even stricter measures and requirements in July 2017.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] However, a motion to that effect, tabled by Esther Ouwehand (PvdD) and Dion Graus (PVV), was voted down by a parliamentary majority of VVD, D66, CDA, CU and SGP.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Farmers' lobby group LTO Nederland opposed obligatory sprinkler systems, arguing these were allegedly insufficiently tested and too expensive, particularly for smaller enterprises, and because 'most barns would never experience fires anyway'.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] LTO was convinced that barns had become safer since the action plan's introduction, but was puzzled why the number of barn fires and victims had only increased afterwards.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In 2018, the Action Plan Fireproof Livestock Barns 2018–2022 was launched, a sequel to the Action Plan Barn Fires 2012–2016.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In the new action plan, the emphasis is on improving the fire safety in existing barns.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Activist group Varkens in Nood ("Pigs in Distress") objected against the optional nature of the proposed measures, and called for extra legal demands.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Since 2009, the Dutch inventors Peter Berlang and Sjaam Hira, in collaboration with the Southeast Netherlands fire brigade and Wageningen University, developed the cable system Stable Safe.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Because firefighters usually took twenty minutes to reach a burning barn, while the animals inside could be dead within ten minutes, this system was invented to let the animals escape the building automatically in the event of a fire.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] As soon as fire is detected, all the dividers and doors fall open and the livestock can escape outside.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The system, which would cost each farm about 10,000 to 20,000 euros, was presented to the Dutch Parliament in 2015.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In a test run, 65% of pigs fled outside, while the rest started to wander about.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The researchers expect that, in a real fire scenario, 90% of the pigs would run for it.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] It would probably not work for chickens, however; when in fear, they tend to lie down flat on the ground.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Just like in pigs, cattle often do not immediately flee when danger presents itself; on the other hand, horses do.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In 2016, a farm in Echt, belonging to the only pork production chain in the Netherlands with a triple star rating from the Dutch Society for the Protection of Animals's "Beter Leven" certification mark, experienced a barn fire, but because the pigs could escape the building, none of them died.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] According to the Dutch Association of Insurers, there were 15 barn fires causing animal fatalities in 2015, 26 in 2016 and 28 in 2017.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Because of a series of alarmingly large-scale barn fires in 2017, particularly in summer with De Knorhof in Erichem as the low point, public debate in the Netherlands broke out on fire safety in barns and animal welfare.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The activist group "Burning Souls" was already founded in January 2017 by Petra Spoor, who was outraged about the fact that the media frequently reported that 'there had been no victims', but there had been hundreds or thousands of dead animals, as if animals weren't 'victims'.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The group holds vigils near burnt-out barns to commemorate the perished animals with flowers, candles and minutes of silence, calls on the national and local authorities to take stricter measures, and on citizens to make their consumption pattern more animal-friendly by eating less or no meat.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] A similar initiative was undertaken by activist group "Eyes on Animals" after the barn fire in Oirschot, claiming the lives of 10,000 pigs in April 2016.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] GeenStijl blogger Bas Paternotte also extended his compassion towards the suffering of animals in July 2017, and criticised the fact that politicians continuously failed to take better measures, although he himself continued to eat meat.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Varkens in Nood launched a citizen's initiative to impose a general professional ban for Adriaan Straathof, owner of De Knorhof, which was signed over 40,000 times, meaning that Parliament had to discuss it.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Straathof already had a professional ban in Germany because of cruelty to animals; Varkens in Nood sought to make that ban Europe-wide.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] As the frequency of prolonged dry spells increases, the risk of barn fires in the UK is rising.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] A review of news media reports from 2013 to 2017 identifies a total of 2.7 million animal deaths in 326 barn fires on American territory.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] This number includes 2.6 million chickens, 71,300 pigs, 34,200 turkeys, 2,600 cows, as well as 1,100 goats and sheep.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Where the cause of the fire is identified, heating equipment is in cause half the time; two-thirds of barn fires occurred between the months of October and March, when the weather is typically colder.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] This also explains why northeastern and midwestern states account for the largest number of reported barn fires involving animal deaths: New York (31), Pennsylvania (29), Michigan (28), Minnesota (26) and Wisconsin (23).
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] This data is incomplete, as no reporting requirements exist for fires involving farm animals.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] One of the National Fire Protection Association's building codes (the NFPA 150) covers specifically animal housing facilities: barns, but also laboratories, kennels, zoos and others.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Its latest revision (published in August 2018) puts more emphasis than previous iterations on agricultural facilities.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] In addition to recommending detection equipment that is currently missing from most installations, the NFPA advocates prevention measures, such as training for employees, inspections and the reduction of combustibles present in and around the facilities to limit the risk of destructive fires.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] The adoption of the NFPA's recommendations by local government, industry and certification programs is voluntary.
[src:rollover-fire/barn-fire] Farm animals are not covered by the federal Animal Welfare Act, which provides some protection to animals in zoos and laboratories, for example.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] A **battalion chief** is the rank and title of a subordinate fire chief or commanding officer in the firefighting command structure.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] The title of battalion chief is usually synonymous with firefighting in the United States and Canada.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] A battalion chief is the lowest chief officer in a fire department's rank structure, above rank-and-file fire station officers and fire company officers.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] A battalion chief is in charge of a firefighting battalion, similar to a military battalion.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] A battalion consists of several fire stations and multiple fire companies.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] A battalion chief has command over each fire station's officers and each company or unit's officers, as well as the uniformed firefighters.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] A battalion chief is usually under the command of a division chief, district chief, deputy chief, or assistant chief, etc who in turn reports to a chief of department, chief engineer, a shift commander, a tour commander or a fire commissioner or other personnel who are official employees.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] Louis Fire Department who all have battalion chiefs in their rank structure.
[src:rollover-fire/battalion-chief] There are several fire departments, including The Boston Fire Department, Denver Fire Department, New Orleans Fire Department and the Toronto Fire Services, however, that use the title of district chief in place of battalion chief.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] The modern firefighter's helmet was developed in 1830 by luggage maker Henry Gratacap, a volunteer firefighter in New York City.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] This helmet is recognizable today as the "New York" style of helmet, and has retained the same basic shape.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] The helmet had a brimmed front to affix a leather shield, usually adorned with a company name and number.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] It featured eight rib sections on the dome for added rigidity and a long rear brim that channeled water away from the wearer's neck.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] The combination of modern triple-layer turnout gear with self-contained breathing apparatus (SCBA), personal alert safety system (PASS) device, and modern communications equipment is intended to provide protection against smoke, heat, water, steam, flashovers, and even direct flame for a short time.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] Modern turnout jackets and pants are made of fire-retardant fabrics, mainly aramids such as Nomex and Kevlar or polybenzimidazole (PBI).
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] In the United States, the National Fire Protection Association publishes the requirements for fire protective clothing under NFPA 1971, *Standard on Protective Ensembles for Structural Fire Fighting and Proximity Fire Fighting*.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] In order to comply with the NFPA standard, protective clothing is required to be tested and certified by independent third-parties, and bear the certifying body's logo and a compliance statement.
[src:rollover-fire/bunker-gear] Such third-party certifications are issued by the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) and UL Solutions.
[src:rollover-fire/rollover-fire] Rollover is not the same as flashover, although it may precede it, and the terms may be confused.
[src:rollover-fire/rollover-fire] In the case of rollover, only gases present in the room, not the room contents, ignite.
